Within the framework of Cold War, Mao pragmatically tried to play off the dominant forces of the Soviet bureaucracy and the US imperialism.
When power struggles broke out within the top ranks of the Chinese Communist Party, Mao launched the "Great Cultural Revolution".
Neither Mao nor Stalin was a real "Marxist" and the clashes were not of a theoretical nature. Mao eulogized Stalin after the latter's death.
Stalin's instructions to submit to the discipline of the KMT in the 1920s had already led to the mass slaughter of the Chinese communists.
Over the thirty year period 1923--1953 until Stalin's death, persistent clashes occurred between the Chinese and Russian Communists.
Mao still held to the theories of class collaboration learnt in the school of Menshevik Stalinism after the World War II ended.
In China this policy directive from Moscow required Mao to form an alliance with Chiang and the Kuomintang against the Japanese.
Indian, VN or Indonesian Communists were ordered to act according to how friendly their colonial masters (UK, FR and NL) were to the USSR.
The CCP was composed primarily of hundreds of thousands of workers in the cities, by 1930 it was made up overwhelmingly of peasants.
When Chiang visited Moscow in 1926, Stalin even made him an honorary member of the Executive Committee of the Communist International.
Marxists traditionally held that socialism would be a world order, based on the highest achievements of mankind as a whole.
The pragmatic plan foresaw the Kuomintang leading a democratic and anti-imperialist revolution, and CCP acting as a pressure group.
Sun Yat-sen until his death in 1925, and Chiang up until 1926, both proclaimed their allegiance to "world revolution" a la Russie.
Chinese nationalism was forced to look to the young Soviet Republic as its only ally against the "democratic" imperialists.
